id: pm-4oio
title: "ADR: SDK author-time helpers are the static inverse of runtime extension checks (deriveâ†”reconcile, describe-blueprintâ†”describe-activation, lintâ†”loader-enforcement+doctor)"
description: "Decision (living ADR): every runtime guardrail the loader/doctor enforces on an activated extension SHOULD have a pure, side-effect-free author-time counterpart in the SDK that operates on the declarative `ExtensionBlueprint` BEFORE activation. The pair is kept honest by a parity/cross-check test rather than by hand.\n\nEstablished pairs:\n- `deriveExtensionCapabilities(blueprint)` (author-time) â†” `reconcileExtensionCapabilityUsage(loaded, activation)` (runtime used-set attribution).\n- `describeExtensionBlueprint(blueprint)` (author-time, pm-tlpv) â†” `describeExtensionActivation(activation)` (runtime, pm-16ue) â€” same `ExtensionActivationSummary` shape, locked by a deepEqual parity test.\n- `lintExtensionBlueprint(blueprint)` (author-time, pm-9ect) â†” the loader's `extension_capability_missing` hard failure + the `pm package doctor` `extension_capability_unused` advisory (pm-fk84).\n\nConsequences: (1) authors and agents catch capability drift, duplicates, and dead declarations at edit/test time, not at load time; (2) drift between the static reimplementation and the runtime is a CI failure (parity test), so the symmetry is maintained by construction â€” the same discipline as the `as const satisfies Record<ExtensionCapability, ...>` exhaustiveness guards already in the codebase; (3) static helpers explicitly cannot reflect the imperative `activate` escape-hatch, and must document that boundary. Aligns with the core philosophy: project management = context management â€” author-time introspection keeps the package surface in the author's context window without paying for activation."
type: Decision
status: closed
priority: 2
